===========================================================================
I. RIEMANN HYPOTHESIS AND THE PALEY TRACE FORMULA
===========================================================================

  The Gauss sum g(p) = Σ χ(a)ω^a satisfies |g(p)| = √p EXACTLY.
  This is the Riemann Hypothesis for y² = x over F_p.

     p       √p     |g(p)|       |g|-√p    Paley |λ|   RH bound
     7   2.6458   2.645751     8.88e-16       1.4142     1.3229
    11   3.3166   3.316625     8.88e-16       1.7321     1.6583
    19   4.3589   4.358899    -1.78e-15       2.2361     2.1794
    23   4.7958   4.795832     5.33e-15       2.4495     2.3979
    31   5.5678   5.567764     0.00e+00       2.8284     2.7839
    43   6.5574   6.557439     8.88e-15       3.3166     3.2787
    59   7.6811   7.681146    -9.77e-15       3.8730     3.8406
    83   9.1104   9.110434     0.00e+00       4.5826     4.5552
   107  10.3441  10.344080     2.84e-14       5.1962     5.1720
   127  11.2694  11.269428    -1.42e-14       5.6569     5.6347

  THOUGHT EXPERIMENT: What if |g(p)| ≠ √p?
  If |g(p)| = p^α for some α ≠ 1/2:
    α < 1/2: Paley eigenvalues SMALLER → even closer to mean → worse for H
    α > 1/2: Paley eigenvalues LARGER → more deviation → could beat Interval
    α = 1/2: the EXACT balance that makes Paley the eigenvector (THM-137)

  WEIL CONJECTURES → TRACE FORMULA:
  For the Paley tournament, the k-th power trace is:
    Tr(A_P^k) = m^k + m·Re[(-1+i√p)^k + (-1-i√p)^k] / 2^k
  The terms (-1±i√p) are the Frobenius eigenvalues of a Hecke L-function.
  Their absolute value is (1+p)^0.5 — this is the ARCHIMEDEAN ABSOLUTE VALUE
  of the Frobenius, controlled by the Weil conjectures.

  INTERVAL EIGENVALUES: sin(jπm/p)/sin(jπ/p)
  These are Dirichlet kernel values — PURELY ELEMENTARY.
  No number theory, no RH, no Weil conjectures needed.
  The Paley→Interval transition is also:
    DEEP ARITHMETIC (RH-dependent) → ELEMENTARY ANALYSIS (Dirichlet kernel)

  DELIGNE'S THEOREM (1974):
    For any smooth projective variety X/F_p of dimension d,
    the eigenvalues of Frobenius on H^i(X) have |α| = p^{i/2}.
  For our 0-dimensional variety (= F_p as a set):
    The Gauss sum is Frobenius on H^1 of the Artin-Schreier cover,
    giving |g| = p^{1/2}. QED.
  This connects tournament combinatorics to étale cohomology!

