  STEP 2: DOMINANT TERM IN THE CYCLE EXPANSION
  For large k, s_k is dominated by the largest eigenvalue ratio.
  Paley: |λ_j/d| = √p/(p-1) → 0 as p → ∞ (ALL terms vanish)
  Interval: |μ_1/d| = (p/π)/(p-1)/2 → 2/π ≈ 0.637 (fixed ratio!)

     p    |λ|/m (P)   |μ₁|/m (I)    ratio
     7     0.440959     0.384127   0.8711
    11     0.331662     0.354947   1.0702
    19     0.242161     0.337530   1.3938
    23     0.217992     0.333816   1.5313
    31     0.185592     0.329484   1.7753
    43     0.156129     0.326179   2.0892
    59     0.132434     0.323951   2.4461
    83     0.111103     0.322269   2.9006

  KEY: Paley's ratio → 0, Interval's ratio → 2/π ≈ 0.637.
  This means for large p:
    s_k(Paley) → 0 exponentially (all terms vanish)
    s_k(Interval) → 2·(2/π)^k · cos(kπ/2 + ...) (persistent)
    The cycle expansion sum Σ s_k/k converges to a POSITIVE constant
    for Interval but to ZERO for Paley.

