ASYMPTOTIC CYCLE EXPANSION: log(H_I/H_P) vs actual
===========================================================================
  p=7: predicted H_I/H_P = 1.009648, actual = 0.925926, error = 0.083723
  p=11: predicted H_I/H_P = 1.043150, actual = 0.978253, error = 0.064897
  p=19: predicted H_I/H_P = 1.054922
  p=23: predicted H_I/H_P = 1.057226
  p=31: predicted H_I/H_P = 1.060057
  p=43: predicted H_I/H_P = 1.062360

  ASYMPTOTIC ANALYSIS:
  As p → ∞:
  s_2 for any tournament: Σ|λ_j/m|² = (p-1)/m → 2
  (This is Parseval: Σ|λ_j|² = p·m, divide by m² and sum p-1 terms)
  So s_2(P) = s_2(I) = 2 (approximately). No advantage at degree 2!

  The advantage comes from HIGHER power sums k ≥ 3:
  p=7: s2=1.3333/1.3333, s3=0.5556/0.5556, s4=0.0370/0.3827
  p=11: s2=1.2000/1.2000, s3=0.3200/0.3200, s4=0.0560/0.4080
  p=19: s2=1.1111/1.1111, s3=0.1728/0.1728, s4=0.0425/0.3900
  p=43: s2=1.0476/1.0476, s3=0.0726/0.0726, s4=0.0215/0.3620
  p=83: s2=1.0244/1.0244, s3=0.0369/0.0369, s4=0.0116/0.3488

  CRITICAL OBSERVATION:
  s_2 is IDENTICAL for Paley and Interval (Parseval constraint)
  s_3 (related to 3-cycles) is ALSO identical (both have same C_3)
  s_4 (related to 4-walks) DIFFERS: Interval has higher s_4
  This is EXACTLY the degree-4 Walsh term that drives the crossover!
  The cycle expansion CONFIRMS the Ising/Walsh picture.

